results.content:
/app/answers.json
{
  "recommendation": "Reduce the starting dose of capecitabine by 50% of the standard dose. Titrate subsequent doses based on tolerability and clinical response. If feasible, therapeutic drug monitoring or phenotyping may guide further dose adjustments. If a fluoropyrimidine is not essential, consider an alternative non-fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy regimen.",
  "classification": "Strong",
  "implication": "An activity score of 1.5 places this patient in the Intermediate Metabolizer (IM) phenotype class, reflecting one normal-function DPYD allele paired with one decreased-function allele (e.g., HapB3/rs75017182 or c.2846A>T/D949V). As demonstrated in the reviewed literature, the HapB3 intronic variant (rs75017182) reduces canonical DPYD mRNA splicing by ~30% and DPD enzyme activity by ~35% (PMID_28295243), while c.2846A>T (D949V) reduces enzyme activity by ~41% (PMID_24648345). Capecitabine is an oral prodrug that is converted in vivo to 5-fluorouracil (5-FU), which is primarily catabolized by DPD. Partial DPD deficiency in this patient will lead to reduced clearance of 5-FU, resulting in elevated plasma drug exposure and substantially increased risk of severe (grade 3-4) fluoropyrimidine-associated toxicity, including mucositis, myelosuppression, hand-foot syndrome, and potentially life-threatening complications."
}

